content.text:
A few options, from most automated to most manual.

**1. Unit-test the ticker helper directly.** `startProgressTick` takes any `io.Writer`, so you can give it a `bytes.Buffer` and skip the TTY gate entirely (that gate is in `Run()`, not in the helper itself). The test exercises exactly the rendering you care about:

```go
func TestProgressTick(t *testing.T) {
    var buf bytes.Buffer
    var counter atomic.Int64

    stop := startProgressTick(&buf, func() string {
        return fmt.Sprintf("discovered %d", counter.Load())
    })

    counter.Add(5)
    time.Sleep(700 * time.Millisecond) // long enough for at least one tick at 500ms
    counter.Add(3)
    time.Sleep(700 * time.Millisecond) // and a second
    stop()

    out := buf.String()
    if !strings.Contains(out, "\r\x1b[Kdiscovered 5") {
        t.Errorf("missing first tick:\n%q", out)
    }
    if !strings.Contains(out, "\r\x1b[Kdiscovered 8") {
        t.Errorf("missing later tick:\n%q", out)
    }
    if !strings.HasSuffix(out, "\r\x1b[Kdiscovered 8\n") {
        t.Errorf("expected final \\r\\x1b[K<line>\\n; got:\n%q", out)
    }
}
```

That tests: tick fires, render is called fresh each time, stop produces one final frame + newline. It's reasonably fast (~1.5 s) and catches changes to the render contract.

**2. Use `os/exec` + a PTY for an integration test.** If you want to verify that `--progress` *plus* TTY detection actually triggers the ticker in `Run()` end-to-end, you need `os.Stderr` to be a real terminal. The standard way is `github.com/creack/pty`:

```go
ptmx, err := pty.Start(exec.Command("./git-sync", "convert-sha256", "--progress", url, dir))
// ptmx now contains everything the child wrote to stderr/stdout
output, _ := io.ReadAll(ptmx)
// assert output contains \r\x1b[K  discovered...
```

This needs a new dependency (`go-git-sync` doesn't currently use creack/pty), and you'd run it under the existing `GITSYNC_E2E_SHA256_HTTP_BACKEND` gate or a new one.

**3. Manual visual verification with `script`.** No code; record a real run to a typescript file using the system `script` utility (available on macOS and Linux), then inspect:

```sh
script -q /tmp/progress.log ./git-sync convert-sha256 --progress \
  https://github.com/spf13/cobra.git /tmp/cobra-progress
cat -v /tmp/progress.log    # see the actual control chars
```

`script` allocates a pty internally, so `isTTY()` is true and the ticker runs. `cat -v` shows the `^M^[[K` sequences plainly.

**Recommendation:** start with option (1) — it's a tight unit test on the actual logic, doesn't need a pty dependency, and verifies the rendering contract. Want me to add it?

